ke contributes the highest proportion to costs, followed by char, anthracite and bituminous coal.}{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s17\cf1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs34\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 From the Commission\'92s report and the other ferrochrome producers\'92 submissions, it would seem that char constitutes between 6% and 8% of the total cost of production of ferrochrome.}}}
{\*\cs34\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up9\rtlch\af11\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af11\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177\cf3 }{\cf3  Coke (having a high carbon content and a lower volatile matter) is always used as a base reductant. }}
